goals.question: What is the distribution of housing prices in the University District?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the range of housing prices in the University District and identify any outliers.

goals.question: What is the relationship between the number of bedrooms and the price of a property in the University District?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of the 'bedrooms' field against the 'price' field
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is a correlation between the number of bedrooms and the price of a property in the University District.

goals.question: What is the most common type of property in the University District?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the distribution of property types in the University District and identify any trends.

goals.question: What is the average rating of properties in the University District?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the distribution of review scores for properties in the University District and identify any outliers.

goals.question: What is the distribution of the distance between properties and the University of Washington?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the proximity of properties to the University of Washington and identify any outliers.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['price'] = pd.to_numeric(data['price'], errors='coerce')
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='price', kde=True, color='blue')
    plt.axvline(data['price'].median(), color='red', label='Median Price: {:.2f}'.format(data['price'].median()))
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('What is the distribution of housing prices in the University District?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['property_type'] = data['property_type'].fillna('Unknown')
    property_type_count = data['property_type'].value_counts()
    property_type_count = property_type_count.reset_index()
    property_type_count.columns = ['property_type', 'count']
    property_type_count = property_type_count.sort_values(by='count', ascending=False)
    property_type_count = property_type_count.head(10)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.barplot(x='property_type', y='count', data=property_type_count, ax=ax)
    ax.set_xlabel('Property Type')
    ax.set_ylabel('Count')
    ax.axhline(y=property_type_count['count'].max(), color='r', linestyle='--', label='Max Count: {:.2f}'.format(property_type_count['count'].max()))
    ax.legend()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['review_scores_rating'] = pd.to_numeric(data['review_scores_rating'], errors='coerce')
    sns.boxplot(x=data['review_scores_rating'], color='lightblue')
    plt.title('What is the average rating of properties in the University District?', wrap=True)
    plt.axvline(x=data['review_scores_rating'].mean(), color='red', label=f"Mean: {data['review_scores_rating'].mean():.2f}")
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
